article.headline: Duquesne 83, St. Bonaventure 67
article.story: EDs: Duquesne 83, St. Bonaventure 67. By ALAN ROBINSON AP Sports Writer PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Duquesne went deep on its bench to make up for the injury absence of shot-blocking Shawn James, returning to its two-unit rotation to quickly open a 14-point lead, and the Dukes went on to beat St. Bonaventure 83-67 on Wednesday night. Kieron Achara had 18 points and 12 rebounds and Duquesne (12-5, 2-2 in Atlantic 10), off to its best start since it had the same record in 1980-81, ended a two-game losing streak despite playing without its leading scorer and rebounder. Michael Lee scored 23 points, but St. Bonaventure (6-12, 0-4) lost its 11th in a row on the road dating to last season and its 10th straight under new coach Mark Schmidt. The Bonnies have lost four in a row overall and seven of eight. Phillip Fayne, who hadn't played since Jan. 2, added 11 points and Bill Clark and Kojo Mensah had 10 each as Dukes coach Ron Everhart went back to the two-platoon system he first introduced at this time a season ago. Duquesne has used that system at times this season, but Everhart has shortened his bench against some opponents when he felt the Dukes had matchup problems. There weren't any in this game as the Dukes used their depth to seize leads of 19-7, 22-9 and 25-11 as backups Fayne, Jason Duty and David Theis combined for 14 of their first 25 points. None of the three had played in Duquesne's last three games, but all 10 Dukes players who appeared in the first half scored by halftime. Duquesne, which lost to the Bonnies at home the previous two seasons, went on a 9-0 run to end the first half and start the second to go up 46-30. St. Bonaventure tried to get back into the game by running off eight in a row to get within nine points at 54-45, but Achara converted a three-point play and hit a free throw and Fayne scored on a driving layup. Achara had 13 points and 11 rebounds in the second half and has 69 points in three games against the Bonnies the last two seasons. The 6-foot-10 James, one of the best shot blockers in NCAA history, sat out with a bruised left kneecap and a sprained knee ligament. His status for Saturday night's game against George Washington is uncertain. Duquesne, one of Division I's worst programs over the last 30 years, needs four more victories for its first winning season since 1993-94. The Dukes have had only two winning seasons in 27 years, the other coming in 1985-86.
